krijk","Chilton, Suffolk, England":"Chilton, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1309–":"1309–Deceased","1309–Female":"1309–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1305–Male":"1305–Deceased","1338–Female":"1338–Deceased","1340–Male":"1340–Deceased","1342–Male":"1342–Deceased","1276–1324":"1276–1324","1276–Female":"1276–Deceased","1338":"1338","1305":"1305","1315":"1315","1324":"1324","1342":"1342","1276":"1276","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1309":"1309","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Woodnorton, Norfolk, England":"Wood Norton, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Chilton, Suffolk, England":"Chilton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Berry","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish and Manx: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Béara</b> ‘descendant of <i>Béara</i>’, a personal name of unexplained etymology; or, in some cases, perhaps an Anglicized form of Irish and Manx <b>Ó Beargha</b>. Compare   Barry   1.","Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Barrie  .","English: habitational name from any of several places called in Devon named with Old English <i>byrig</i>, dative case of <i>burh</i> ‘fortified manor house, stronghold’, such as Berry Pomeroy and Berrynarbor."],"variants":[{"name":"Berrey","meanings":["English: variant of   Berry  ."]},{"name":"Barry","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Donal, Aidan, Ciaran, Eoin, John Patrick, Kaitlin, Kieran, Murphy, Aileen, Brigid, Caitlin.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Beargha</b> ‘descendant of <i>Beargh</i>’, a byname meaning ‘plunderer’.","Irish and Manx: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Báire</b> ‘descendant of <i>Báire</i>’, a short form of either of two Gaelic personal names, <i>Bairrfhionn</i> or <i>Fionnbharr</i>, both meaning ‘fair-topped’. This may also be the source of the Manx name <i>Barry</i>, whose family's main seat was Ballavarry in Kirk Andreas."]},{"name":"Bery","meanings":["English: variant of   Berry  .","Hungarian (<b>Béry</b>): habitational name for someone from any of various places called Bér, in Baranya, Komárom, Nógrád, Pest, Vas, or Zala counties."]},{"name":"Beery","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of <b>Ó Béara</b>. See   Berry   and   O'Berry  .","Americanized form of Swiss German   Bieri  ."]},{"name":"Berrie","meanings":["Scottish:","(Glasgow): from Middle English or Older Scots <i>(atte) beri</i> ‘(at the) manor house’, see   Berry  .","variant   Barrie  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":6,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":19,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":73,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Berry was born in 1309, in Chilton, Suffolk, England, her father, Sir/Knight Edmund De Berry, was 33 and her mother, Alice Gerbridge, was 33. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with John Crane."},"et":{"1309–":"1309–Surnud","1309–Female":"1309–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1305–Male":"1305–Surnud","1338–Female":"1338–Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1342–Male":"1342–Surnud","1276–1324":"1276–1324","1276–Female":"1276–Surnud","1338":"1338","1305":"1305","1315":"1315","1324":"1324","1342":"1342","1276":"1276","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1309":"1309","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Woodnorton, Norfolk, England":"Wood Norton, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Chilton, Suffolk, England":"Chilton, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1309–":"1309–Kuollut","1309–Female":"1309–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1305–Male":"1305–Kuollut","1338–Female":"1338–Kuollut","1340–Male":"1340–Kuollut","1342–Male":"1342–Kuollut","1276–1324":"1276–1324","1276–Female":"1276–Kuollut","1338":"1338","1305":"1305","1315":"1315","1324":"1324","1342":"1342","1276":"1276","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1309":"1309","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Woodnorton, Norfolk, England":"Wood Norton, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Chilt